The paper deals with wireless network transmissions and their feasibility, which falls under the category of information theory (cs.IT) and networked systems (cs.NI). The use of graphs to model wireless receptions and interference suggests a connection to graph theory (cs.DS), while the exploration of the limits of graph representations and the cost of abstraction relates to computational complexity and optimization (cs.SI). Finally, the use of a family of conflict graphs and the analysis of approximation algorithms suggests a connection to machine learning and data analysis (cs.LG).
